ation. AIM allows merchants to host their own secure payment form and send transactions to the payment gateway using an end-to-end secure sockets layer (SSL) connection.','How to install the Authorizenet AIM payment module','','publish','open','open','','how-to-install-the-authorizenet-aim-payment-module','','','2012-06-14 05:26:29','2012-06-14 05:26:29','',0,'http://blog.tomatocart.com/?p=7',0,'post','',0),(22,1,'2012-06-14 06:27:41','2012-06-14 06:27:41','Developing A Module Within The TomatoCart Admin Panel has been a popular request by the Community. As an example, outlined below is used to illustrate the development process of the \'Currencies\' module in \'\'Admin Start Menu-&gt;Definitions-&gt;Currencies\'.\n\nThrough this example, we are going to demonstrate:\n\n--How to build a new menu in the start menu.\n\n--How to build a window.\n\n--How to build a grid in the window.\n\n--How to integrate the add, edit and delete functionalities into grid.\n<h6>Figure 1. Currencies Module (Start Menu -&gt; Definitions-&gt;Currencies )</h6>\n<img src=\"http://farm6.staticflickr.com/5463/7186078957_fb85e1014e_n.jpg\" alt=\"Currencies\" />\n<h3>Getting Started</h3>\nTo begin, we need to add a \'Currencies\' menu in the \'Definitions\' menu as shown in figure 2.\n<h6>Figure 2. Add a \'Currencies\' Menu</h6>\n<img src=\"http://farm6.staticflickr.com/5039/7186082289_1ca6a4c497.jpg\" alt=\"currencies-admin\" />\n\nIn order to add the \'Currencies\' menu, it is necessary do the steps as follows:\n\n--create a currencies.php in \'admin/includes/modules/access\' directory.\n--create a class which is inherited from osC_Access class in the currencies.php:\n<h6>Figure 3. Create osC_Access_Currencies Class</h6>\n<code>class osC_Access_Currencies extends osC_Access {\nvar $_module = \'currencies\',\n$_group = \'definitions\',\n$_icon = \'currencies.png\',\n$_title,\n$_sort_order = 200;</code>\n\nfunction osC_Access_Currencies() {\nglobal $osC_Language;\n\n$this-&gt;_title = $osC_Language-&gt;get(\'access_currencies_title\');\n}\n\n<address><strong>Note:</strong> if the module name have more than a word, you should use the underscore character</address><address>between them. For example, \'orders_status.php\'.And, it is necessary to uppercase the first</address><address>character of each word in the module name for the class name.So, the class name should be</address><address>composed of two parts: osC_Access and module name, one underscore should be added</address><address>between them.In this case, it is \'osC_Access_Currencies\'. If the module name is \'orders_status\',</address><address>the class name should be \'osC_Access_Orders_Status\'.</address><address> </address><address>In the osC_Access_Currencies class, there are five properties:\n$_module -- It holds the module name.$_group --It holds the group name that the module should belongs to. In this case , the value is\n\'definitions\'. It means that the \'currencies\' module should locate in the \'definitions\' group.\nFigure2 has illustrated it.$_icon -- It just holds the icon name. But, actually, the menu icon of the currencies isn\'t decided\nby this property.In fact, it is decided by the css \'.icon-currencies-win\'. If the module name is\n\'orders_status\', the css should be \'.icon-orders_status-win\'. We will discuss it in details below.$_title -- It holds the menu title of the module. In this case, it should be \'Currencies\'. We will\ndiscuss it again later.$_sort_order -- It decides the position of the menu. For example, in the Definition group menu,\nthere are Information menu and Currencies menu etc. The value of the $_sort_order is 100 in the\nosC_Access_Information class and 200 in the osC_Access_Currencies class. As a result Information\nmenu is displayed first than the Currencies menu. It means that lowest of the sort order is displayed\nfirst. Note: if the value of the $_sort_order has already been used by one module, the module with the\nsame value of the $_sort_order will be displayed last.--create a currencies.php in \'admin/includes/languages/en_US/modules/access/\' directory. In this file,\nwe could add the language definitions for the Currencies menu. As we can see in the figure 3. The value\nof the title property is initialized by $osC_Language-&gt;get(\'access_currencies_title\'). So we just need\nto add a language definition key \'access_currencies_title\'  into the currencies.php as figure 4 shown.</address>\n<h6>Figure 4. Add access_currencies_title language key and the correlative value.</h6>\n<code>access_currencies_title = Currencies</code>\n\nAs a result, the menu title is \'Currencies\' as we can seen it in figure 2.\n\n--add the icon css in \'admin/templates/default/desktop/css/icon.css\'. For currencies module, we have said\nthat the icon is decided by the \'.icon-currencies-win\' css class.It is necessary to add this class into\nicon.css and set a background image for it as below.\n<h6>Figure 5. Add Icon Css</h6>\n<code>.icon-currencies-win {background-image: url(\'/../../images/icons/16x16/currencies.png\') !important;}</code>\n\n<em>Note: we add the !important at the end of the css sentence to ensure the useful of the icon css.The icon\nimages should be put in \'admin/templates/default/images/icons/16x16\'.</em>\n\nAfter doing these steps, the currencies menu should be displayed in the \'Start Menu -&gt; Definitions\' menu\nas the figure 2 shown.\n<h3>Create The Window For The Module</h3>\nOnce add the menu successfully, it is time to build the window for the module. For the currencies module,\nas we can see from the Figure 1, when the Currencies menu is clicked, one window include a grid panel will\npop up.How to create this window? Let\'s do it.\n\nFirstly, it is necessary to create a currencies directory in \'admin/includes/extmodules/\' directory.\n\n<em><strong>Note:</strong> the name of the directory should be same as the module name.</em>\n\nSecondly, create a main.php in the currencies directory. At the top of the file, it must set a name\nspace for this module. In this case, we add the name space as follows:\n\n<code>echo \'Ext.namespace(\"Toc.currencies\");\'</code>\n\nWith this new name space, we could add the new class in this name space like Toc.currencies.CurrenciesGrid.\nWe will talk about it later.\n\nThe main.php includes all the javascript about this module. Once the menu have been clicked, all the js code\nincluded in the main.php will be loaded and eval. And, the createWindow method will be called automatically.\nThen, the window of the module will be displayed.\n<h6>Figure 6. Diagram illustrates the sequence of creating window</h6>\n<img src=\"http://farm6.staticflickr.com/5038/7371323750_898ab5bcca_n.jpg\" alt=\"Pic\" />\n\nThirdly, override the createWindow method of the TocDesktop.CurrenciesWindow in main.php.In fact, after we add\nthe currencies menu, the TocDesktop.CurrenciesWindow class is constructed automatically, it is extended from\nthe Ext.app.Module.\n<h6>Figure 7. Override the createWindow method of the CurrenciesWinow in main.php</h6>\n<code>Ext.override(TocDesktop.CurrenciesWindow, {</code>\n\ncreateWindow : function() {\nvar desktop = this.app.getDesktop();\nvar win = desktop.getWindow(\'currencies-win\');\n\nif(!win){\nwin = desktop.createWindow({\nid: \'currencies-win\',\ntitle: \'get(\"heading_title\"); ?&gt;\',\nwidth: 800,\nheight: 400,\niconCls: \'icon-currencies-win\',\nlayout: \'fit\'\n});\n}\n\nwin.show();\n}\n});\n\nAs we can see, it just need to use the Ext.override method to override the createWindow method of the\nTocDesktop.CurrenciesWindow. So when the user click the \'Currencies\' menu, these code will be loaded and eval.\nThen this createWindow method will be called automatically to construct the window and show it.\n\nIn the createWindow method,we get the desktop object and call the getWindow method of the  desktop object to\nget the currency window whose id is \'currencies-win\'. If we can\'t get it, it is necessary to call the\ncreateWindow of the desktop object to create the currencies window.It just need to pass a json object to\nconfigure the window. The id of the window is \'currencies-win\'. Its width is 800 and height is 400.\nThe iconCls \'icon-currencies-win\' is responsible for setting the icon at the top left corner of the window.\nIn this case , the icon is just same as the icon of the currencies menu.The title of the window is get by the\n$osC_Language object with the \'heading_title\' key.All the language definitions for the currencies module should\nbe loaded from the currencies.php in \'admin/includes/languages/en_US/\' directory. So we create it and create the\nlanguage key and value in it as follow:\n<h6>Figure 8. Add the heading_title language definition in \'admin/includes/languages/en_US/currencies.php\'</h6>\n<code>heading_title = Currencies</code>\n\n<code></code>\n<em>Note: If the module is \'orders_status\', the window class will be TocDesktop.OrdersStatusWindow. It means that we\nneed to delete the underscore between the word of the module name and uppercase the first character of each word.\nAnd, the language definitions for the menu of the module should be defined in admin/includes/languages/en_US/\nmodules/access/module.php .The language definitions for the module should be defined in admin/includes/languages\n/en_US/module.php(replace the module with the module name, for example, currencies).</em>\n\nNow, the currencies window should looks like:\n<h6>Figure 9. The Currencies Window Without Any Data</h6>\n<img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7073/7186121081_d120d2f13c_n.jpg\" alt=\"pic2\" />\n<h3>Create A Grid In The Window</h3>\nSince we just create a window for the module in the previous steps, it\'s time to create a grid so that the data\nfor the module could be displayed in the window.\nFirst of all, we need to create a currencies_grid.php in \'admin/includes/extmodules/currencies/\' directory.\nAs you can see, the file name is composed of the module name, underscore and \'grid\'.\nSecondly, in the currencies_grid.php, we create the Toc.currencies.CurrenciesGrid class which is extended from\nExt.grid.GridPanel.\n<h6>Figure 10. Create the Toc.currencies.CurrenciesGrid class</h6>\n<code>Toc.currencies.CurrenciesGrid = function(config) {\nconfig = config || {};</code>\n\nToc.currencies.currenciesGrid.superclass.constructor.call(this, config);\n};\n\nExt.extend(Toc.currencies,CurrenciesGrid, Ext.grid.GridPanel, {});\n\nAs we can see from the figure 10, we define a constructor called Toc.currencies.\nCurrenciesGrid and it is possible to pass a configure object to it.\nIn the constructor, the superclass\'s constructor will be called with the scope of the CurrenciesGrid and the config object.\nBefore running the code in the constructor, we have use Ext.extend method to extend the Toc.currencies.CurrenciesGrid from\nthe Ext.grid.GridPanel. It means that the property and methods of the Ext.grid.GridPanel could be called from the\nconstructor of Toc.currencies.CurrenciesGrid.\nIt is also possible pass the customized method for the Toc.currencies.currenciesGrid to the third params.\nIn this case, we just pass a empty object.So when new a Toc.currencies.CurrenciesGrid object, the code in the constructor\nwill run. The Toc.currencies.currenciesGrid.superclass is pointed to the Ext.grid.GridPanel.Its constructor will be called\nwith the scope of new object and the config object.\n\nThirdly, we must configure the grid panel. It just need to pass the configurations to the config object as\nproperties because the config object will be passed to the superclass\'s constructor. In that constructor,\nextjs will extract the properties of the config object and set it as properties of the grid panel.\nOkay, let\'s add some configurations as follows:\n<h6>Figure 11. Add Border, viewConfig, ds configurations For Grid Panel</h6>\n<code>config.border = false;\nconfig.viewConfig = {emptyText: TocLanguage.gridNoRecords};</code>\n\nconfig.ds = new Ext.data.Store({\nurl: Toc.CONF.CONN_URL,\nbaseParams: {\nmodule: \'currencies\',\naction: \'list_currencies\'\n},\nReader: new Ext.data.JsonReader({\nroot: Toc.CONF.JSON_READER_ROOT,\ntotalProperty: Toc.CONF.JSON_READER_TOTAL_PROPERTY,\nid: \'currencies_id\'\n}, [\n\'currencies_id\',\n\'title\',\n\'code\',\n\'value\',\n\'example\'\n]),\nautoLoad: true\n});\n\n\'config.border\' is used to make the grid\'s border display or hide.\n\n\'config.viewConfig\' is used to set the empty text when there isn\'t any data in the grid.\n\n\'config.ds\' is used to build a data store for the grid based on the ajax technology.In this case,\nthe ajax request is sent to Toc.CONF.CONN_URL which is equal to \'json.php\'. The baseParams will be posted to\njson.php which is in \'admin/\'. In json.php, the module and action params will be got. Then, the currencies.php\nin \'admin/includes/jsons/\' will be included and the \'listCurrencies\' method will be called to return the data\nthat will be shown in the grid.\n\n<address><strong>Note:</strong> the underscore in the action param should be deleted and use the camel word form.For example,</address><address>list_currencies should become listCurrencies, update_currency_rates should become updateCurrencyRates.</address>The Reader is used to read the data returned by the ajax request.It means that the root of the data is \'records\'\nand the totalProperty of the data is \'total\'. Every record(row) is composed of currencies_id, title, code, value,\nexample.The json data returned from the ajax request should be formatted as follows:\n<h6>Figure 12. The Json Data</h6>\n<code>{\'total\': value, \'records\':[{\'currencies_id\':value, \'title\': value, \'code\': value, \'value\':value, \'example\': value }, {\'currencies_id\':value, \'title\': value, \'code\': value, \'value\':value, \'example\': value }]}</code>\n\nAfter adding the data store of the grid, it is necessary to add the action buttons for the grid row.We will add\nthe delete and edit buttons for the row as follows:\n<h6>Figure 13. Add The Delete And Edit Buttons</h6>\n<code> config.rowActions = new Ext.ux.grid.RowActions({\nActions: [\n{iconCls: \'icon-edit-record\', qtip: TocLanguage.tipEdit},\n{iconCls: \'icon-delete-record\', qtip: TocLanguage.tipDelete}\n],\nwidthIntercept: Ext.isSafari ? 4 : 2\n});\nconfig.rowActions.on(\'action\', this.onRowAction, this);\nConfig.plugins = config.rowActions;</code>\n\nWhen you want to add the delete and edit buttons for the row, please just copy the code in Figure 13 and put them\ninto the constructor. The delete and edit handlers will be illustrated later.\n\nNext, we need to add the column headers and selections for the grid as follows:\n<h6>Figure 14. Add The Column Headers And Selections</h6>\n<code>Config.sm = new Ext.grid.CheckboxSelectionModel();\nConfig.cm = new Ext.grid.ColumnModel([\nConfig.sm,\n{id: \'currencies_title\', header: \'get(\'table_heading_currencies\'); ?&gt;\', dataIndex: \'title\'},\n{header: \'get(\'table_heading_code\'); ?&gt;\', dataIndex: \'code\'},\n{header: \'get(\'table_heading_value\'); ?&gt;\', dataIndex: \'value\'},\n{header: \'get(\'table_heading_example\'); ?&gt;\', dataIndex: \'example\'},\nconfig.rowActions\n]);</code>\n\nAs the figure 14 demonstrated, we create a selection module which is responsible for outputing the check boxes at\nthe start of the every row.Then, we map the column header with the data store and the header title should be\ndefined in currencies.php in \'admin/includes/languages/en_US/\' as follows:\n\n<code>table_heading_currencies = Currencies\ntable_heading_code = Code\ntable_heading_value = Value\ntable_heading_example = Example\ntable_heading_action = Action</code>\n\nAt last, we add the rowAtions which is defined in figure 13.\n\nFinally,the top bar and bottom bar need to be configured. Here, we will not show the detailed code. Please see the\nsource code in the project.When you need to add top bar and bottom bar into the grid panel, please copy the\ncorrelative code to your constructor. It will be available for you.\n\nAfter doing the configurations for the gird as above, we need to add the handlers for the buttons in the grid.\nAll the handlers should be configured in the third parameter of the Ext.extend method.Here, as a example,\nwe just add the delete handler as follows:\n<h6>Figure 15. Add The Delete Handlers</h6>\n<code>Ext.extend(Toc.currencies.CurrenciesGrid, Ext.grid.GridPanel, {\nonDelete: function(record) {\nvar currenciesId = record.get(\'currencies_id\');\nvar code = record.get(\'code\') ;</code>\n\nExt.MessageBox.confirm(\nTocLanguage.msgWarningTitle,\nTocLanguage.msgDeleteConfirm,\n\nFunction(btn) {\nIf (btn == \'yes\') {\nExt.Ajax.request({\nurl: Toc.CONF.CONN_URL,\nparams: {\nmodule: \'currencies\',\naction: \'delete_currency\',\ncID: curreciesId,\ncode: code\n},\nCallback: function(options, success, response) {\nvar result = Ext.decode(response.responseText);\n\nIf (result.success == true) {\nthis.getStore().reload();\n}else {\nExt.MessageBox.alert(TocLanguage.msgErrTitle, result.feedback);\n}\n}\n});\n}\n}\n);\n}\n});\n\nIn the onDelete handler, we get the currencies code and id with the record.get method. When the delete button\nin the grid row is clicked, the record of the row will pass into the onDelete handler.After that, we pop up a\nconfirm message box. Once the user confirm it, we will send a ajax request to the currencies module and call\nthe deleteCurrency action with the cID and code parameters.If the delete action is successful, the data store\nof the grid will be reloaded so that the data in the grid will be refreshed.\n\nNow, let\'s see the json files that are responsible for handling the ajax request.\n<h3>Create Json File For Handling The Ajax Request</h3>\nLet\'s create a json file for the currencies module as follows:\n--create a currencies.php in \'admin/includes/jsons/\' directory.\n--create a class name toC_Json_Currencies.\n--create the listCurrencies and deleteCurrency method in the class.\n<h6>Figure 16. toC_Json_Currencies class</h6>\n<code>Class toC_Json_Currencies {\nFunction listCurrencies() {</code>\n\n}\n\nFunction deleteCurrency() {\n\n}\n}\n\nAs we have mentioned before, when a ajax request is sent to the json.php with the module and action parameters,\nif the module is currencies and the action is list_currencies, the listCurrencies method of the\ntoC_Json_Currencies class will be called.In this method, we will not illustrate the detailed code.\nIt just get the needed data and return the data as a json string.\n\n<address><strong>Note: </strong>The json class is composed of toC_Json_ and the module name .The first character of the word in the module\nname should be capitalized. If the module is orders_status, the json class should be toC_Json_Orders_Status.\nThe underscore between the words of the action should be deleted and make it in a camel form. For example,\nif the action is delete_currency, it should become deleteCurrency in the json class.</address><address> </address>Once all the previous things completed, it should construct a grid object and add it into the window.\n<h3>Construct A Grid Object And Make It As A Item Of The Window</h3>\nSince we have successfully created a grid class in \'currencies_grid.php\', the file should be included at the top\nof the main.php so that we could use the class to construct a grid object.Let\'s do it as below:\n<h6>Figure 17. Include The Grid Class In Main.php</h6>\n<code>require_once(\'currencies_grid.php\');</code>\n\nNow, the Toc.currencies_CurrenciesGrid class is available. We could construct the object as below:\n<h6>Figure 18. Construct The Grid</h6>\n<code>if(!win){\ngrd = new Toc.currencies.CurrenciesGrid({owner: this});</code>\n\nwin = desktop.createWindow({\nid: \'orders_status-win\',\ntitle: \'<!--?php echo $osC_Language--->get(\'heading_title\'); ?&gt;\',\nwidth: 800,\nheight: 400,\niconCls: \'icon-currencies-win\',\nlayout: \'fit\',\nitems: grd\n});\n}\n\nAs we can see from the figure 18, we construct a grid and set it as one item of the window. The owner is passed\nto the grid so that in the grid, the window object could be referenced.\n\nNow, the window should looks like the figure 1.\n<h3>Conclusion</h3>\nOver this example, you got a crash course in these aspects:\n--How to build a new menu in the start menu.\n--How to build a window.\n--How to build a grid in the window.\n--How to integrate the add, edit and delete functionalities into grid.\n\nPlay with it, and see what you think!','Tutorial: Developing A Module Within The TomatoCart Admin Desktop','','publish','open','open','','tutorial-developing-a-module-within-the-tomatocart-admin-desktop','','','2012-06-14 06:27:41','2012-06-14 06:27:41','',0,'http://blog.tomatocart.com/?p=22',0,'post','',0),(210,1,'2012-06-14 06:29:18','2012-06-14 06:29:18','Hello TomatoCart translators,\n\nThe first thing I would like to say is \"thank you so much”. Thank you for helping TomatoCart growing day by day. Your help and contribution make it possible for TomatoCart to reach out to the world.\n\nNow, we are proud to announce that the Romanian language pack is downloadable at<a title=\"Extension Manager\" href=\"http://www.tomatocart.com/index.php/products/extension-manager?task=view&amp;id=184\"> Extension Manager</a>for out-of-the-box installation. It must be uneasy to make the stone roll. There are totally 3,750 items! Yet you guys get it done. A good job!\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff9900;\"><strong>Special thanks to: </strong></span>\n<span style=\"color: #ff9900;\">hhhans2</span>, who translated<span style=\"color: #ffcc00;\"> </span><span style=\"color: #8a2be2;\"><span style=\"color: #ff9900;\">2173</span><span style=\"color: #000000;\"> i</span></span><span style=\"color: #000000;\">tem</span>s in all;\n<span style=\"color: #ff9933;\"><span style=\"color: #ff9900;\">urecheatu007</span><span style=\"color: #000000;\">,</span> </span><span style=\"color: #ff9